{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645023"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:11:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:11:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18078"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18078"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.07,0,0,0.82]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10792"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75879"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10792"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18078"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61392"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5677"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25146"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25977"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75879"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man is brought to the emergency department by police officers for assessment of abdominal pain. He is currently under arrest and in police custody. The police officers request to remain in the examination room during the medical assessment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial response?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Allow officers to observe from within the examination room","Examine the patient only with a chaperone present","Postpone examination until after release from custody","Decline to examine the patient while in custody","Request officers to wait outside unless there is a security risk"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate response is to \u003Cstrong\u003Erequest officers to wait outside unless there is a security risk\u003C/strong\u003E. Healthcare providers have the same duty of care to patients in custody as to any other patient, including the right to a private medical consultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllow officers to observe from within the examination room\u003C/strong\u003E - This would breach patient privacy and confidentiality, potentially preventing the patient from discussing medical concerns openly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecline to examine the patient while in custody\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents discrimination and fails to meet the required duty of care to the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExamine the patient only with a chaperone present\u003C/strong\u003E - While a chaperone may be appropriate, this response does not address the fundamental issue of police presence during the consultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPostpone examination until after release from custody\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents an inappropriate delay in providing necessary medical care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf there are legitimate security concerns, officers should be positioned outside the room within easy reach. If this is unachievable due to significant safety risks, employing techniques that still allow the patient privacy during examination should be utilised (e.g. having curtains drawn between police and the patient). They may only be present during examination if there is a significant and immediate risk to staff safety that cannot be managed by other means.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Healthcare providers have the same duty of care to patients in custody as to any other patient.","Medical examinations of patients in custody must be conducted in private, without police or corrections officers present unless there is a significant security risk.","Patient confidentiality applies equally to patients in custody, with limited exceptions for mandatory reporting requirements."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119","Medical care in police custody. Royal College of Pathologists Australia. 2019. Available from: https://www.rcpa.edu.au/getattachment/e06d0128-fc73-47c9-a5e9-8eaf836b1883/Medical-Care-in-Police-Custody.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61392"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18078"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61392"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T07:54:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T07:54:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10792"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75879"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCo